    "narrative": "Today\u2019s offensive engine is anchored by **Austin Riley** (71.53) and **James Wood** (69.33), our two strongest plays. **Austin Riley** benefits from a high-upside matchup against Jake Irvin; despite a slight negative adjustment for the catcher's pop time, his premium spot in the order combined with the favorable xERA of 4.92 makes him a must-start. **James Wood** is equally compelling, buoyed by a +10% order boost as the leadoff hitter against Elder. His ability to capitalize on the 4.29 xERA allows him to contribute significantly across our categories, particularly in Runs, which remains a key focus for Ghost Ride the WHIP.\n\nThe decision to bench **Kyle Karros** (44.18) was the closest call of the morning. While **Kyle Karros** offers some value against the lefty Wrobleski, his efficiency score fell behind our starters due to a bottom-third batting order placement and a negative adjustment for the pitcher's elite skill level. Elsewhere, we are monitoring the matchup for **Vinnie Pasquantino** (53.20); while his raw talent is evident, he faces the toughest test of the day against Kyle Bradish (2.63 xERA). We are relying on his +14% platoon edge to keep his production viable. Meanwhile, **Dalton Rushing** (54.21) remains a marginal start, as he is hampered by a difficult lefty-on-lefty matchup against Quintana. Managers should note that with **Corbin Carroll**, **Jose Caballero**, and **Mickey Moniak** all unavailable today, our depth is being tested, requiring us to lean heavily on the remaining active roster to maintain our pace in the 5x5 standings.",
